I do understand the desire for a more diverse character pool though, but we did legitimately get Symetra and Torb play yesterday, so....
Also, by the end of day 2 of the season, every single hero had been played. We even saw some incredibly effective Symmetra play from the @ SFShock last night.
Used to be one player got 1 or 2 good picks and it was time to reset. You're seeing much more coordinated team play now and teams are able to stay in the fight even after losing 2 players.
But for now, I'm still loving it. It's still the first weekend. I think everyone is playing it safe, keeping with the meta, trying to start off strong.

But more so than that, some of the strategies really blew me away. LA Gladiators on Kings Row in the post season comes to mind. I feel like there will be a team this season (hopefully Vancouver) that will break the meta and maybe GOATS will be less prevalent.

We dealt with mercy meta stage 1 last year which drew all fights out. We dealt with dive comp most of season one. I have no problem dealing with goats now. I feel more skill is on display in these team fights now.
But I dont think it's on Blizzard to change the game to stop teams from sticking with this comp. We've seen some good counters and will continue to see more throughout the stage.

As a player, I totally understand wanting to see a bigger hero pool. A lot of what made season 1 so insane was watching players execute shit that I couldn't even fathom doing. Jjonak especially really opened my eyes.

I mean I’m not trying to knock player skills, my issue is more so with blizzard not being able to balance it out. And like I’m not even looking for flashy plays, I just wanna see how these pros utilize different characters so I can learn how different ones play off each other
Most importantly, give me all the http://D.Va bombs.
And we are seeing some good minor variations. Great when seeing teams counter with the Sombra. And we have seen a couple quad dps comps so far.

I equate this to the average fight fan getting bored with ground game because they want to see knockouts. Those of us that train understand the intricacies of what's going on in the jujitsu ground game.
We're not getting highlight reel plays, but some quality team fights that come down to solid team play and comms and separating enemy players. A lot of skill on display.

Honestly, at first I thought it was going to bog down play, but 3/3 is really just a way more calculated game. Sure, we don't have a ton of flashy Widow and Tracer plays, but its still the same insane level of skill and game IQ as last season. I believe @ FloydtheRover would agree
